{{Infobox Artwork | image_file = A palace concert.jpg | painting_alignment = | image_size = 400px | title = A Palace Concert | other_language_1 = Chinese | other_title_1 = 宮樂圖 | other_language_2 = | other_title_2 = | artist = Unknown | year = Unknown | type = Ink and colors on silk | height_metric = 48.7 | width_metric = 69.5 | height_imperial = | width_imperial = | metric_unit = cm | imperial_unit = in | city = [[Taipei]] | museum = [[National Palace Museum]] }} '''''A Palace Concert''''' ({{zh|宮樂圖}}) is a Chinese [[Tang Dynasty]] [[silk painting]] showing ten [[Court lady|court ladies]] and two standing servant maidens around a large rectangular table. Some court ladies are depicted drinking tea, while others drink wine. The four women at the far end are presumably responsible for playing music and livening up the mood. The musical instruments depicted, from left to right, are bamboo pipes, [[guqin]], [[pipa]] and [[flute]]. One of the servant maidens plays a [[Clapper (musical instrument)|clapper]] to maintain beat. A small dog is depicted under the table. The artist and the precise year of the painting are unknown. The painting is housed in the [[National Palace Museum]] in [[Taipei]], Taiwan.
==Dating== The hairstyles are combed in one direction on top, while others are combed in two directions and tied into knots around the ears. In addition to a floral headdress, these all indicate some of the popular Tang dynasty fashions.<ref name="com">{{cite web | url =http://www.chinaonlinemuseum.com/painting-anonymous-a-palace-concert.php|title=A Palace Concert|publisher=China Online Museum|accessdate =30 April 2016}}</ref> The woven bamboo table, cusped crescent stools, winged wine cups and the style of the lute playing with a large pick showcase late Tang dynasty customs.<ref name="com"/>
