{{Infobox Theatre |name = Theatre Royal, Cork |image = |caption = |address = George's Street (now Oliver Plunkett Street) |city = [[Cork (city)|Cork]] |country = [[Ireland]] | coordinates = {{Coord|51.897829|-8.470485|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} |latitude = |longitude = |architect = |owner = |pushpin_map = Ireland |capacity = 2,000 |type = [[patent theatre]] |opened = 1760 |yearsactive = 1760–1840; 1867–75 |rebuilt = 1853 |closed = 1875 |othernames = |production = |currentuse = General Post Office |website = }}
The '''Theatre Royal''' was a [[patent theatre]] located in [[Cork (city)|Cork City]], Ireland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lookandlearn.com/history-images/U305794/The-New-Theatre-Royal-Cork?img=46075&bool=phrase|title=The New Theatre Royal, Cork|publisher=}}</ref>
==History==
The Theatre Royal was founded by local actor [[Spranger Barry]] in 1760. It was modelled on the [[Crow Street Theatre]], [[Dublin]].
The theatre was destroyed by fire on [[April Fool's Day]] 1840. In 1853 it was rebuilt, and in the 1860s it was [[Renovation|refurbished]] under the direction of [[John Benson (architect)|Sir John Benson]], and re-opened on 26 December 1867.
In 1875 the theatre was sold to the postal service and Cork's GPO opened on the site in 1877.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archiseek.com/2011/1867-theatre-royal-cork/|title=1867 - Theatre Royal, Cork - Architecture of Cork City, Lost Buildings of Ireland - Archiseek - Irish Architecture|date=15 January 2011|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://irishamericancivilwar.com/2015/10/09/the-polopticomorama-bringing-the-american-civil-war-to-life-in-irish-theatres-1863/|title=The ‘Polopticomorama’: Bringing the American Civil War to Life in Irish Theatres, 1863|date=9 October 2015|publisher=}}</ref> The last three plays performed were [[James Sheridan Knowles]]' ''Virginius''; [[William Shakespeare]]'s ''[[Hamlet]]''; and [[John Wilson (playwright)|John Wilson]]'s ''Belphegor''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.ie/books?id=sRxmCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT104&lpg=PT104&dq=%22Theatre+Royal,+Cork%22&source=bl&ots=T2K9iiKVoq&sig=tbiS21fYSxOjdYMVK8h_V1Hbd8o&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjlv7XArOHUAhXHKsAKHV11AEwQ6AEITTAJ#v=onepage&q=%22Theatre+Royal,+Cork%22&f=false|title=Little Book of Cork|first=Kieran|last=McCarthy|date=7 September 2015|publisher=History Press|via=Google Books}}</ref>
==Description== An 1867 description from the ''[[Illustrated London News]]'': {{Quote|The theatre is constructed to hold two thousand persons, and is divided into two tiers of [[Box (theatre)|boxes]], a capacious [[Orchestra pit|pit]], [[Theater_(structure)#Seating_and_audience|stalls, private boxes, and a spacious gallery]], from which latter “[[Wiktionary:coign of vantage|coign of vantage]]” an excellent view of the [[Stage (theatre)|stage]] is afforded, while the tenants of the boxes are screened from the view of [[The gods (theatrical)|the god]]s – an important consideration in a town where gallery criticism is often extended unceremoniously to the well-dressed class of visitors.<ref>http://www.corkpastandpresent.ie/history/illustratedlondonnews/cork-relatedexcerptsfromtheillustratedlondonnews/1866-1885/cork_theatre_royal_p560_1867.pdf</ref>}} ==References== {{reflist}}
